
Q1. Classical Arabic Secondry Phonemes?
As noted by Bloomfield (1933), Secondry Phonemes are not part of any simple (e.g. alphabet compsing a syllables) meaningful
speech-form taken by itself, but appear only when two or more are combined into a larger form, or else when speech-forms
are used in certain ways-- especially as sentences. 


________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
The follwoing is based on Bloomfield (1933), Aronoff (1976), & McCarthi (1989 & 1985).
Arabic language combines tense with aspect (how an action unfolds over time):

Perfective (completed actions) vs. Imperfective (ongoing/habitual actions)
Example in Arabic:
Perfective (Past): كَتَبَ (kataba – "he wrote")
Imperfective (Present/Future): يَكْتُبُ (yaktubu – "he writes/will write")
 													
